<h2>Event in February 2021</h2>
<br><br>
Most striking event in this winter month was the remarkable eruption (linked to the sudden stratospheric warming) of very cold weather early February followed by extreme mild spring conditions in the second half of the month.
<br><br>
In Germany, in the week beginning 8 February, the temperature fell below -20&deg;C at many observing stations, breaking monthly records, whilst even low-lying areas received heavy snow, according to the Deutsche Wetterdienst. Canals in the Netherlands froze over with scating Dutchmen everywhere in the country an increasingly rare event. This was followed by unusually mild weather in central Europe. GÃ¶ttingen in Germany saw a massive (and record) temperature difference of 41.9&deg;C in the space of less than a week in February, swinging from -23.8&deg;C on 14.02.21 to 18.1 &deg;C on 21.02.21, according to DWD.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/feb2021/Analyse_20210212.png"><img alt="" src="../images/feb2021/Analyse_20210212.png" width="350px"></a>
<a href="../images/feb2021/Analyse_20210221.png"><img alt="" src="../images/feb2021/Analyse_20210221.png" width="350px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1: Weather maps of 12 and 21 February 2021 made by KNMI, with in a week a change from deep winter into exceptional mild spring conditions</em>
<br><br>
The United Kingdom saw its coldest February night since 1955, with the temperature in Braemar, Aberdeenshire fell to -23.0 &deg;C on 10 February, according to the UK Met Office.
In Scandinavia, Latvia saw an average air temperature in winter 2020/2021 of -3,7 &deg;C, the coldest since 2012/2013, and also with the thickest snow cover since then. In the first ten days of February the average air temperature in Latvia was -8.8 &deg;C, which is 5.0 &deg;C below the decade norm (1981-2010 norm)
<br><br>
<h2>Specific climate indicators for February 2021</h2>
<br><br>
As described in the previous section, temperatures over parts of Europe varied considerably during the month of February, due to a change of the prevailing atmospheric circulation pattern mid of the month.
Over Germany and the Benelux countries, for example, this resulted in more than12 more warm days than normal (the 1981-2010 average), but at the same time also in up to 12 more cold nights than normal as visible in Figures 2 and 3. Large parts of central and eastern Europe also saw both exceptionally above normal maxima and exceptionally below normal minima temperatures (see Figure 7). New station records for the month of February occurred in many countries, as well as record warm February days/nights both in lowlands and highlands. Some countries also saw new national February records for maximum temperature such as Sweden, Poland, Slovakia, Slovenia and Croatia.
